body:
invoke this action with `-p N 30` -> success
with `-p N 512` -> failure, specifically
```
 "result": {
            "error": {
                "code": "EMFILE",
                "errno": -24,
                "path": "DATA",
                "syscall": "open"
            }
        }
```

here is the code
```
var fs = require('fs')

function main(params) {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
	fs.writeFile('DATA', 'LOTS OF FILES!!!!', function(err) {
	    if (err) {
		reject(err)
	    }
	    
	    var latch = params.N
	
	    function read() {
		fs.readFile('DATA', 'utf8', function(err, contents) {
		    if (err) {
			reject(err)
			
		    } else if (--latch === 0) {
			resolve({N: params.N})
		    }
		});
	    }
	    
	    for (let i = 0; i < params.N; i++) {
		read()
	    }
	});
    });
}
```

This is an inadvertent breaking change in that my intention was to preserve the previous behavior but I did not have the right test in place. I've addressed the issue with this proposed change (and the accompanying test): https://github.com/openwhisk/openwhisk/pull/1579/commits/cffa53bdaf679cd7fe825a06a5d587d680bfee88#diff-c7a6ca91e16420b15c39ab67b4584401R289).

However, after further consideration, allowing this for rules only is asymmetric - in that for other API operations that have references to entities, we do require a fully qualified name. This is true for a sequence components and for a package binding. Hence for consistency, I am inclined to close as won't fix in the API and instead resolve by documenting that a CLI upgrade is required instead.

